<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="220" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[178,1085,1467,1518]" pageId="13" pageNumber="220">Etymology: The specific epithet (Latin, adjective: wedge-shaped) alludes to the conspicuous shape of the median lobe of the aedeagus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="221" pageId="13" pageNumber="220" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[178,1086,1533,1584]" lastBlockId="14.[178,1084,219,270]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="221" pageId="13" pageNumber="220">
Description: Body length 5.0- 
<quantity box="[609,701,1533,1555]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4" pageId="13" pageNumber="220" unit="mm" value="5.4">5.4 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity box="[951,1082,1533,1554]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="13" pageNumber="220" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.3" valueMin="2.2">2.2-2.3 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: head blackish, pronotum blackish-brown to blackish, elytra dark-yellowish; abdomen dark-brown to blackish, with the posterior margins of the segments narrowly brownish; legs yellowish; antennae blackish, with antennomere I paler brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[178,1086,285,424]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[247,321,285,307]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) noticeably transverse; dorsal surface with distinct microreticulation, subdued shine, and very fine and sparse, barely noticeable punctation. Eyes large, much longer than postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[776,854,344,366]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) slender, 
<quantity box="[964,1086,344,366]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" unit="mm" value="1.6" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="1.5">1.5-1.7 mm</quantity>
long; preapical antennomeres very weakly transverse; antennomere XI elongated and apically acute.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[178,1085,440,520]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[295,372,440,462]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) 1.20-1.25 times as broad as long and approximately 1.35 times as broad as head, subject to weakly pronounced sexual dimorphism; disc with pronounced microreticulation and subdued shine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[178,1085,536,587]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[258,335,536,558]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as pronotum; punctation dense and fine; interstices with distinct microreticulation and subdued shine. Hind wings fully developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[178,1086,602,712]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Abdomen with fine, but distinct transverse microsculpture; tergites III-VII impunctate near anterior margins; tergites III-VI with moderately dense, tergite VII with sparser punctation on remainder of surfaces; pubescence predominantly composed of short and rather stout brownish setae; tergite VII without sexual dimorphism.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[178,1086,727,983]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">
♂: pronotum with weakly granulose punctation only in postero-median portion, remainder of disc with fine and non-granulose punctation; tergite III with weakly pronounced median tubercle; tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[503,582,786,808]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) with broadly and distinctly concave posterior margin; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[425,508,815,837]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) transverse, somewhat longer than tergite VIII, and strongly convex posteriorly; median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[755,869,844,866]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Figs 21-22</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" unit="mm" value="0.75">0.75 mm</quantity>
long and of very conspicuous shape, particularly in lateral view: in the middle with pronounced wedge-shaped protrusion, ventral process distinctly bisinuate in lateral view, crista apicalis narrow, but pronounced; paramere (
<figureCitation box="[695,769,932,954]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) large and approximately 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" unit="mm" value="0.75">0.75 mm</quantity>
long, apical lobe with conspicuously long and black subapical seta.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[178,1085,999,1138]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">
<specimenCount box="[178,199,1004,1025]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: pronotum with fine, non-granulose punctation; tergite III with or without median tubercle (similar to that of male); posterior margin of tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[852,926,1028,1050]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
) truncate in the middle; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[420,500,1057,1079]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
) distinctly transverse and with broadly and distinctly convex posterior margin, submarginal setae only indistinctly modified; spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[185,296,1116,1138]" captionStart="Figs 17-28" captionStartId="12.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1079,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 17-28: Nepalota cuneata nov.sp.: (17) male forebody; (18) antenna; (19) male tergite VIII; (20) male sternite VIII; (21-22) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (23) paramere; (24) female tergite VIII; (25) female sternite VIII; (26-28) spermatheca. Scale bars: 17: 1.0 mm; 18: 0.5 mm; 19-28: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414176/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Figs 26-28</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity box="[463,552,1116,1137]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" unit="mm" value="0.31">0.31 mm</quantity>
long, of very variable shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="221" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[178,1085,1153,1351]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">
Comparative notes: As can be inferred from the similar sexual and external characters, particularly the presence of a sexual dimorphism of the pronotum, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2015" box="[975,1085,1183,1204]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nepalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneata">
<emphasis box="[975,1085,1183,1204]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">N. cuneata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely allied to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="1987" box="[374,464,1212,1233]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nepalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="franzi">
<emphasis box="[374,464,1212,1233]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">N. franzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[516,641,1212,1233]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nepalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis box="[516,641,1212,1233]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">N. chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs by the slightly more slender pronotum, the less extensively granulose punctation of the male pronotum, by the shapes of the male tergite and sternite VIII, the conspicuous morphology of the aedeagus, the shape and chaetotaxy of the female sternite VIII, and by the shape of the spermatheca.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="221" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="14.[178,1086,1374,1484]" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">
Distribution and natural history: The known distribution is confined to several localities in 
<collectingRegion box="[504,584,1404,1425]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[598,668,1403,1425]" captionStart="Map 4" captionStartId="13.[178,223,877,898]" captionTargetBox="[178,1082,212,868]" captionTargetId="figure-1@13.[178,1082,212,868]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Map 4: Distributions of Nepalota yunnanensis PACE (filled circles), N. cuneata nov.sp. (open circles), and N. crocea nov.sp. (star) in China, based on examined records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414180" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414180/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">Map 4</figureCitation>
). The specimens were sifted from sifting leaf litter in various forest habitats at altitudes between 2290 and approximately 
<quantity box="[1001,1081,1432,1454]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.65" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" unit="m" value="2650.0">2650 m</quantity>
, partly together with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="1998" box="[384,505,1462,1483]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nepalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="221" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="smetanai">
<emphasis box="[384,505,1462,1483]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="221">N. smetanai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
